Repository Best Practices for Collaborative Projects

When multiple team members work on the same project, especially a large model training and post-analysis project, poor planning and unstructured collaboration can lead to inefficiency, frustration, and mistakes. To address this, we recommend adopting branching strategies and collaboration guidelines at the start of every project. This document outlines best practices to ensure efficient and organized teamwork.

1. Plan the Project Workflow and Branching Strategy

Define the Project Workflow

	•	Break Down the Project into Phases:
	•	Examples: Data extraction, preprocessing, exploratory analysis, model training, post-analysis, reporting.
	•	Identify Independent and Dependent Tasks:
	•	Independent: Tasks that can proceed without blocking others (e.g., data cleaning, initial EDA).
	•	Dependent: Tasks that rely on the completion of others (e.g., training the model depends on data preprocessing).

Create a Branching Plan at the Start

	•	Branch Types:
	•	main: Stable branch for production-ready code.
	•	develop: Integration branch for combining new features and updates.
	•	feature/*: For independent tasks or features (e.g., feature/data_cleaning, feature/model_training).
	•	task/*: For specific sub-tasks within features, when tasks are highly dependent (e.g., task/preprocess_data_for_model under feature/model_training).
	•	hotfix/*: Urgent fixes for production issues.
	•	report/*: For sections of the final report (e.g., report/model_performance).

Best Practices for Branching

	1.	Collaborators Shouldn’t Work in the Same Branch: Assign each team member their own branch (e.g., feature or task branches) to avoid conflicts.
	2.	Group-Dependent Work:
	•	Use a shared branch (e.g., feature/model_training) for closely related tasks, but coordinate updates and commits using a branch owner.
	•	Regularly synchronize with the parent branch (develop).
	3.	Establish Milestone Tags:
	•	Use tags for significant progress points (e.g., v1.0-data-cleaned, v2.0-model-trained).

2. Define Commit and Merge Guidelines

Commit Guidelines

	•	Frequency: Commit often to save progress but only after testing small changes locally.
	•	Atomic Changes: Each commit should focus on one logical change (e.g., fixing a bug, adding a new function).
	•	Descriptive Commit Messages: Use clear and meaningful messages (e.g., feat: add data preprocessing script).

Pull and Merge Guidelines

	•	Regular Pulls: Sync your branch with the latest updates from develop daily or before starting work.
	•	Conflict Management:
	•	Resolve conflicts locally and ensure the code works before pushing changes.
	•	Test merged code thoroughly to avoid downstream errors.
	•	PR Reviews:
	•	Define clear reviewers and approvers for each PR.
	•	Use a checklist for PR reviews (e.g., “Code style followed?”, “Are tests passing?”, “Does it introduce new issues?”).

3. Collaborating on Reports

Challenges of Collaborative Reporting

Reports often involve interdependent sections (e.g., data summaries, model performance, recommendations). Without coordination, multiple contributors can create conflicts or duplicate work.

Best Practices for Reports

	1.	Divide the Report into Sections:
	•	Create separate files for different sections (e.g., 01_introduction.Rmd, 02_EDA.Rmd, 03_model_training.Rmd).
	•	Assign owners to each section.
	2.	Use Branching for Report Changes:
	•	Example:
	•	report/eda_summary
	•	report/model_results
	•	Merge report branches into a shared report branch regularly.
	3.	Track Report Dependencies:
	•	Use comments in the code or Confluence to document which analyses feed into which sections of the report.

4. Recommended Git Workflow for Team Projects

	1.	Start the Project:
	•	Create main and develop branches.
	•	Set up a Confluence page to document the branching strategy and task assignments.
	2.	Assign Tasks:
	•	Divide the work into features and tasks.
	•	Assign branches to team members:
	•	Example:
	•	Person A: feature/data_cleaning
	•	Person B: feature/model_training
	•	Person C: report/model_performance
	3.	Develop in Parallel:
	•	Work in individual branches and commit often.
	•	Pull updates from the parent branch (e.g., develop) daily to minimize merge conflicts.
	4.	Merge Changes:
	•	Submit PRs to develop when a task or feature is complete.
	•	Assign reviewers and ensure all tests pass before merging.
	5.	Testing and Review:
	•	Use automated tests for consistent validation of changes.
	•	Manually review PRs for critical tasks (e.g., model performance evaluation).
	6.	Finalize and Deploy:
	•	Merge develop into main after completing all features and passing final tests.
	•	Tag the release (e.g., v3.0-final-report) for future reference.

5. Key Tips for Efficient Collaboration

Plan Dependencies Early:

	•	Use project management tools (e.g., JIRA, Trello) to track dependent tasks and deadlines.

Automate Where Possible:

	•	Automate repetitive tasks (e.g., preprocessing pipelines, report rendering) to reduce workload.

Weekly Syncs:

	•	Hold regular team meetings to review progress, resolve bottlenecks, and plan next steps.

